-- Endesa, Portugal Telecom, Santander, Repsol, EDP: Iberian Equity Preview
-- Adam Ewing
-- 2010-06-21T06:33:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-21/endesa-portugal-telecom-santander-repsol-edp-iberian-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Spanish and Portuguese trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close.  
 Spain’s  IBEX 35  Index rose 2.2 percent to 9,971.8.
Portugal’s  PSI-20  Index gained 2.5 percent to 7,411.32.  
 Spanish stocks:  
 Banco Santander SA  (SAN SM): The lender is considering
selling parts of its U.K. operations in a share sale, the  Times 
reported, without saying where it got the information. Santander
declined to comment on talk it’s being advised by Credit Suisse
Group AG about a U.K. share sale, according to the report. Any
public offering in Britain is unlikely to happen this year, the
newspaper said. The shares climbed 3.5 percent to 9.35 euros.  
 Endesa SA  (ELE SM): The power producer holds its annual
shareholders’ meeting. The shares increased 2.2 percent to 19.19
euros.  
 Repsol YPF SA  (REP SM): The oil company was raised to
“buy” from “neutral” at Banesto Bolsa, which cited the
prospects of its operations in Brazil, according to a note sent
to investors. The shares rose 1 percent to 17.825 euros.  
 Sniace SA (SNC SM): The company and partners Banco
Santander and Helium won a contest to develop 190 megawatts of
wind power in Cantabria in northern Spain. The shares climbed
3.1 percent to 1.303 euros.  
 Portuguese stocks:  
 EDP-Energias de Portugal SA  (EDP PL): Portugal’s biggest
power company was rated “overweight” at Banesto Bolsa with a
price estimate of 3.17 euros. The shares rose 0.9 percent to
2.61 euros.  
 Portugal Telecom SGPS SA  (PTC PL): Tele Norte Leste
Participacoes SA, known as Oi, asked Brazil’s President  Luiz Inacio Lula  da Silva to help prevent Portugal Telecom from
making a bid for control of the Brazilian phone company, O
Estado de S. Paulo said, citing a person “close to the
government” that it didn’t name. Lula agreed that the company
shouldn’t be sold to a foreign group, the newspaper reported.
Portugal Telecom shares advanced 1.6 percent to 8.839 euros.  
